        </p>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="row">
    <div class="col-12 tutorial-para">
        <p>
            As mentioned earlier, Bootstrap 4 offers a grid system for making content suitable for both desktop and mobile. There are a few rules that need to be considered when using the grid system:
        </p>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="row">
    <div class="col-12 tutorial-para">
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    Columns (class=”col”) <strong>must be</strong> direct children of rows
                </li>
                <li>
                    Columns within a particular row cannot exceed 12
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="row">
    <div class="col-12 tutorial-para">
        <span><strong>Step 1: Create Row</strong></span>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="row">
    <div class="col-12 tutorial-para">
        <p>
            As stated in the rules of the grid system, if we want to use columns we first need to create a row to contain them. Select an view you want that uses the view that references Bootstrap 4 as its layout.
            For this tutorial I will be using the Index page. Add a div tag to your chosen page which has the class “row” as shown below:
        </p>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="row">
    <div class="col-6">
        <pre>
        <code class="language-html">
        &lt;div class="row"&gt;

        &lt;/div&gt;
        </code>
        </pre>
    </div>
    <div class="col-6 tutorial-para">
        <p>
            The code to the left will not do anything in particular just now. The class informs the DOM that the div is a Bootstrap row
        </p>
    </div>
</div>

